<div id="review_985607378" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/985607378" />
    <a title="Murtaza " class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/13716226-murtaza"><img alt="Murtaza " src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1531516448p2/13716226.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/985607378?book_show_action=true">Jul 03, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Murtaza " class="user" itemprop="url" name="Murtaza " href="/user/show/13716226-murtaza">Murtaza </a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer985607378" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2644415832435555536">Frantz Fanon&apos;s writing is always bristling with a particular type of clinical anger. His heritage as both a physician and a revolutionary is very evident in his prose. In some ways philosophic anti-colonial works such as these feel dated, but at the same moment timeless. The same psychological habits which pervaded the world a few short decades ago - stark racism, bigotry and hypocrisy among them - continue to live on, although clothed in different garb.<br/><br/>There&apos;s not so much to say about this work</span>
  <span id="freeText2644415832435555536" style="display:none">Frantz Fanon's writing is always bristling with a particular type of clinical anger. His heritage as both a physician and a revolutionary is very evident in his prose. In some ways philosophic anti-colonial works such as these feel dated, but at the same moment timeless. The same psychological habits which pervaded the world a few short decades ago - stark racism, bigotry and hypocrisy among them - continue to live on, although clothed in different garb.<br /><br />There's not so much to say about this work at this point; it's short, pointed, and somewhat convoluted. It complements The Wretched of the Earth well, and perhaps its most poignant and memorable quality is what it stands for as a symbol than what it argues itself. Psychoanalysis itself is a field which has faded from prominence since this work was written, so the long passages expounding about it in this context came across as dull. Fanon makes an heartfelt call at the end for a new, mutually respectful and constructive relationship to develop between whites and blacks. I didn't expect this, given the vituperative stance taken in the rest of the book and in other works, but it was rather impressive.</span>
  <a data-text-id="2644415832435555536" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


