              <span id="reviewTextContainer34231366" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9001485482196266682">I have to admit that I&apos;ve always been skeptical of the works of psychology. I think it has to do with how we met (first incarnated in my high-school psychologist that was mainly concern in showing us how to use a pad and latter in my stereotype of female psychology undergrads always fashionably uniformed).<br/><br/>But, my late readings of books or articles that use either psychological or psychoanalytical theories have proof me wrong. It is time to let those images go. No prior judgment. Psychosis is eve</span>
  <span id="freeText9001485482196266682" style="display:none">I have to admit that I've always been skeptical of the works of psychology. I think it has to do with how we met (first incarnated in my high-school psychologist that was mainly concern in showing us how to use a pad and latter in my stereotype of female psychology undergrads always fashionably uniformed).<br /><br />But, my late readings of books or articles that use either psychological or psychoanalytical theories have proof me wrong. It is time to let those images go. No prior judgment. Psychosis is everywhere. <br /> <br />Fanon is an unique case. He uses a prose deep rooted in the I. His discussion on the colonial subject surely brings more than economic exploitation. There is always desire, recognition, self-mutilation, self-magnification at the time of contact. He reminds us that inferiority is not just but the other side of superiority: it's validation. <br /><br /><br /> </span>
  <a data-text-id="9001485482196266682" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

